    <br />

    
    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Privacy Provision and Location Verification in Wireless Networks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Liza M Kunjachen</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Privacy Provision<br />Wireless Networks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2009 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P4414</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Our proposals will show a new approach for secure localization and location verification in wireless networks which is based on hidden and mobile base stations. In this approach localization means compute the correct location of a trusted device in the presence of an attacker, which will be done by using broad spread spectrum technique, ultrasonic or radio frequencies. The location verification, means verify or compute the location of an un-trusted device, which will be done based on the received signal strength or signal time of flight from a node to base stations. This approach is based on hidden mobile stations. Hidden mobile stations are nothing but covert base stations (CBS), whose locations are not known by the attacker at the time of the execution of the secure localization, CBS’s are silent on the wireless channel, they only listen to the ongoing communication. We also propose how the localization schemes are securable from both internal and external attackers. In this project, the protocol makes certain that a node cannot lie about its position. Thus we propose to show, how the security of this approach depends on the precision of the localization and ranging techniques of systems and on the number of covert base stations. We propose to show with several examples, how these approaches can be used in node-centric and infrastructure-centric localization schemes. Infrastructure-centric localization systems are those in which the infrastructure computes the locations of nodes based on their mutual communication. We describe a simple solution for securing infrastructure-centric localization systems based on Time difference of arrival (TDOA) and CBS’s, and the node-centric localization system, we mean that a node computes its position by observing the signals received from public base stations (PBS’s) with known location and we present a protocol, named as position verification protocol for secure localization in node-centric localization systems. Finally our proposals have to show, how the position verification schemes can be applied in mobile ad hoc networks.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10185">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10185</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/5531">M.Tech</a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
